<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="secA2-Midterm2Review" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Midterm #2 Review</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            The second midterm exam will cover material from Week 5 Day 1 of the class through Week 7 Day 2. 
            That is, it covers material in the following sections: 
            <ul marker="">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec26-LinearTransformations"/> Linear Transformation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec31-CofactorExpansion"/> Determinants
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec32-DeterminantsInverse"/> Properties of Determinants
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec41-VectorsLines"/> Vectors and Lines
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec42-ProjectionsPlanes"/> Projection and Planes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec51-SubspaceSpanning"/> Subspaces
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <xref ref="sec52-IndependenceDimension"/> Independence and Dimensions
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            On this page, you will find review problems for the midterm exam. 
            The final answers are included for each problem.
            Make sure you spend some time working through these problems and understanding how things work! 
        </p>

        <p>
            <alert>A quick reminder:</alert> The class session before the midterm exam #2 on Tuesday, May 19, will be a review session. 
            Usually this will be a work day for you to work through some problems together to prepare for the exam. 
            This is also a great opportunity for you to ask questions about anything that is not clear to you! 
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <worksheet xml:id="ws-MidtermReview-LinearTransformations">
        <title>Linear Transformations</title>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>T: \R^3 \to \R^2</m> be a linear transformation such that
                <md>
                    T \lp \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ -3 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix}2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
                    \, , \quad
                    T \lp \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix}0 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
                    \, , \, \text{ and } \quad
                    T \lp \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 3 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} \rp = \begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                Find a matrix <m>A</m> such that <m>T</m> is defined by the formula <m>T(\v{x}) = A\v{x}</m>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} -2 \amp -4 \amp 19 \\ -7 \amp -12 \amp 59 \end{bmatrix}</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </worksheet>

    <worksheet xml:id="ws-MidtermReview-Determinants">
        <title>Determinants (and related stuff)</title>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 5 \\ 2 \amp 3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                Find <m>\det A</m> using (1) the cofactor expansion, and (2) elementary row operation to convert the matrix into upper triangular form. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>\det A = 50</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </worksheet>

    <worksheet xml:id="ws-MidtermReview-VectorGeometry">
        <title>Vector Geometry</title>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Determine whether the lines <m>\v{p}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ -1 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\v{p}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} + s \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ -2 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}</m> intersect, and if so, find the point of intersection.
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    The two lines are parallel of each other. 
                    Hence they do not intersect. 
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Determine whether the lines <m>\v{p}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} </m> and <m>\v{p}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 0 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix} + s \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 4 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> intersect, and if so, find the point of intersection.
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    They intersect at the point <m>\lp 3,4,7 \rp</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Determine whether the lines <m>\v{p}_1 = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\v{p}_2 = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix} + s \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> intersect, and if so, find the point of intersection.
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    These two lines do not intersect. They are skew. 
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        
        <exercise>
            <p>
                Write the equation of the plane with normal vector <m>\v{n} = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</m> passing through the point <m>\lp 4,1,5 \rp</m>. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>-x + 2y + z = 3</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        
        <exercise>
            <p>
                Find an equation of the plane that contains the points <m>(1,2,3)</m>, <m>(-1,0,4)</m>, and <m>(1,1,1)</m>. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>5x - 4y + 2z = 3</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Find an equation of the plane passing through the three points <m>P = (1,0,0)</m>, <m>Q = (0,1,1)</m>, and <m>R = (2,0,1)</m>. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>x + 2y - z = 1</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Find the intersection of the line <m>\v{p} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} + t \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 2 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> and the plane <m>x + y + z = 14</m>. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>(1,5,8)</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>\v{p}</m> denote the line of intersection of the planes <m>x - y - z = 1</m> and <m>2x + 3y + z = 2</m>. 
                Find an equation for the line <m>\c{p}</m> in parametric form. 
            </p>
        </exercise>
    </worksheet>

    <worksheet xml:id="ws-Subspaces">
        <title>Subspaces (and related stuff)</title>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 4 \amp 0 \amp -30 \amp 6 \\ 3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 5 \amp -1 \\ 6 \amp 6 \amp 0 \amp -30 \amp 21 \\ 3 \amp 2 \amp 0 \amp -5 \amp 5 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                Find a basis and the dimension of the null space and the column space of <m>A</m>. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    Basis for <m>\Col A = \left\{ \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \\ 6 \\ 3 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 1 \\ 6 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ -1 \\ 21 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix} \right\}</m> and <m>\dim \Col A = 3</m>. 
                </p>

                <p>
                    Basis for <m>\Nul A = \left\{ \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} -5 \\ 10 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} \right\}</m> and <m>\dim \Nul A = 2</m>. 
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Determine if the following set 
                <md>
                    U = \left\{\begin{bmatrix} x \\ 0 \\ z \end{bmatrix} \mid x^2 + z^2 = 0 \text{ and } x,z \in \R\right\}
                </md>
                is a subspace of <m>\R^3</m>. 
                Justify your reasoning. 
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    Yes
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Determine which of the following sets are bases for <m>\R^2</m> or <m>\R^3</m>. 
                Justify your reasoning. 
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\left\{\begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 10 \\ -3 \end{bmatrix}\right\}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\left\{\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ -7 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 5 \\ -5 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}\right\}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\left\{\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -8 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ 2 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix}\right\}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                This is a basis for <m>\R^2</m>. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                This is NOT a basis for <m>\R^2</m> nor <m>\R^3</m>. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                This is NOT a basis for <m>\R^2</m> nor <m>\R^3</m>. 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Let <m>A = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp -3 \amp -4 \\ -8 \amp 8 \amp 6 \\ 6 \amp -7 \amp -7 \end{bmatrix}</m>. 
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find a basis for <m>\Col A</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Is <m>\v{p} = \begin{bmatrix} 6 \\ -10 \\ 11 \end{bmatrix}</m> a vector in <m>\Col A</m>? 
                            Justify your reasoning. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <answer>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            A basis for <m>\Col A</m> is <m>\left\{ \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -8 \\ 6 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 8 \\ -7 \end{bmatrix} \right\}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Yes <m>\v{p}</m> is in <m>\Col A</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise>
            <p>
                Find a basis for the subspace spanned by the following vectors:
                <md>
                    \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \\ 2 \\ -4 \end{bmatrix}\, , \, 
                    \begin{bmatrix} -3 \\ 9 \\ -6 \\ 12 \end{bmatrix}\, , \, 
                    \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 4 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}\, , \, 
                    \begin{bmatrix} -4 \\ 5 \\ -3 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix}
                </md>
                Then determine the dimension of this subspace. 
            </p>
        </exercise>

        <answer>
            <p>
                A basis is <m>\left\{ 
            \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \\ 2 \\ -4 \end{bmatrix}, 
            \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1 \\ 4 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}, 
            \begin{bmatrix} -4 \\ 5 \\ -3 \\ 7 \end{bmatrix} 
            \right\}</m>
            and the dimension is <m>3</m>
            </p>
        </answer>
    </worksheet>

</section>